From: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
Date: Fri, 6 Mar 2026 17:07:53 -0800
Subject: [PATCH] ==== failed region charge rate ====

mm/damon: introduce DAMOS failed region quota charge ratio

One common issue we get reported from DAMON users is that the progress
speed of DAMOS is sometimes get much slower than expected.  For example,
a group of users reported they tried to run DAMOS-based proactive memory
reclamation with DAMOS quota of 100 MiB per second.  The users set the
quota because they don't didn't want too radical change on the system.
There was no running workload so they were pretty sure all memory is
cold, and actually they were able to show the system reclaims about 100
MiB memory per second.  But from a point, the reclamation speed was
significantly dropping down time to time.

A theory that can easily explain this is that the quota was exceeded
with memory that the reclamation was failed.  DAMOS tries to apply the
user-requested action to all access pattern matching memory, up to the
quota per quota interval (100 MiB per second in the above example).
DAMON region is set by only access pattern, not based on other
information like whether the memory is reclaimable or not.  Hence
applying the DAMOS action to a DAMON region can fail for some parts of
the region.

Using DAMOS, users can apply specific system operation (DAMOS action) to
memory regions having access pattern of their interests.  For example,
reclaiming memory that not accessed for two minutes or longer.  On
systems and workloads that have dynamic access pattern, static DAMOS
target access pattern could impose unexpected radical impacts.

To avoid such undesired aggressive behavior, DAMOS quota feature is
introduced.  It allows users to set the upper-limit memory amount that
the system operation action can be applied in a give time period.  In
other words, it sets maximum aggressiveness of a given DAMOS scheme.

DAMOS action is applied to all entity of memory region of the access
pattern.  For some of the entity, however, the action can fail.  For
example, pageout DAMOS action will fail for mlock()-ed pages in the
region.  Meanwhile, all entities that the action was tried to be applied
are samely charged for the quota, regardless of the successfulness of
the attempt.

The charging rule arguably makes DAMOS quota difficult to understand and
finely control.  Let's suppose there is a system having 1 GiB memory,
and the 500 MiB memory at the end of the physical address space is
mlock()-ed.  Entire memory is cold, and the user runs DAMOS-based
proactive reclamation with a quota, say, 100 MiB per second.  The user
will see the system is reclaiming 100 MiB memory per second, for the
first five seconds.  But, for the following five seconds, DAMOS will
attempt to reclaim the cold memory of the mlock()-ed region, fail, and
only up to 100 MiB per second.  From user's perspective, it would look
like DAMOS stopped working.  If the mlock()-ed region is randomly
scattered around, the progress of the reclamation would look only very
unpredictable to the user's perspective.

Someone coudl argue the quota is working as documented and designed.
It also provides DAMOS stat, which shows amount of memory that applying
the action was successful and failed.  The user can understand the
situation by reading the stats.  That is, it is not a bug but a feature.

But, the stat feature is not really helpful in this situation.  Afte
all, monitoring DAMOS stat is arguably additional work for the users.
Also, the DAMOS action progress depends on not only the quota, but also
the access pattern.  Users should suspect and investigate two factors to
understand the situation.  In many case this is not very simple.  Even
if users figure out the situation is due to the quota and action-failed
memory, there is no many things that the user can easily do to change
the situation.

Worse yet, the behavior is not really helpful for the initial intent:
aggressiveness.  The basic idea behine the current behavior was that,
even for action-failed memory, some of the overhead may be induced, so
better to charge the memory in an extent.  We simply started with an
extent that is same to that for the action successfully applied memory.
In the real world, however, the overhead for action failed regions is
much smaller than that for action succeeded regions.  For the above
example, for mlock()-ed pages, DAMOS will just see it is mlock()-ed and
skip to next page.  Meanwhile, for action-successful memory, it will
also check if it is mlcok()-ed, and do the costly pageout work.

So it still makes sense to charge some of the quota for the
action-failed memory.  But, charging it same as the action-success
memory is not fair.

Let users set the charge ratio for the action-failed memory, by
specifying the numerator and denominator of the ratio.  For example,
let's suppose the ratio is set to 1/4,096.  A DAMOS scheme action is
applied to 5 GiB memory.  For 1 GiB of the memory, the action is
succeeded.  For the rest (4 GiB), the action is failed.  Then, only 1
GiB and 1 MiB quota is charged.

The optimal charge ratio will depend on the use case and
system/workload.  I recommend to starting from 1/4,096, since must DAMOS
actions are applied in page granularity, and many systems have 4 KiB
page size.

Tests
=====

I tested this feature in below steps.

1. Allocate 50% of system memory and mlock() it using a test program.
2. Fill up page cache to exhaust nearly all free memory.
3. Start DAMON-based proactive reclamation with 100 MiB/second
   hard-quota.  Auto-tune the soft-quota under the hard-quota for
   achieving 40% free memory of the system with 'temporal' tuner.

For the step 1, I used a simple C program that written by Gemini.  It is
too simple, so I'm not sharing the code here.

For the step 2, I use dd command like below:

   dd if=/dev/zero of=foo bs=1M count=$50_percent_of_system_memory

For the step 3, I use the latest version of DAMON user-space tool (damo)
like below.

    sudo ./damo start --damos_action pageout \
            ` # Do the pageout only up to 100 MiB per second `
            --damos_quota_space 100M --damos_quota_interval 1s \
            ` # Auto-tune the quota below the hard quota aiming` \
            ` # 40% free memory of the node 0 ` \
            ` # (entire node of the test system)` \
            --damos_quota_goal node_mem_free_bp 40% 0 \
            ` # use temporal tuner, which is easy to understnd ` \
            --damos_quota_goal_tuner temporal

As expected, the progress of the reclamation is not consistent, because
the quota is exceeded for the failed reclamation of the unreclamable memory.

I do this again, but with failed region charge ratio feature.  For this,
the above 'damo' command is used, after appending below command line option.
Note that the option was added to 'damo' after v3.1.9.

    sudo ./damo start --damos_action pageout \
            [...]
            ` # quota-charge only 1/4096 for pageout-failed regions ` \
            --damos_quota_fail_charge_ratio 1 4096

As expected, the progress of the reclamation was nearly 100 MiB per
second until the goal is achieved.

